Through statistical analyses, we uncover subtle associations and potential predictive patterns, shedding light on the nuanced interplay between lifestyle choices and cardiovascular outcomes. Emphasizing the significance of modifiable risk factors, such as diet and physical activity, our findings underscore the importance of proactive measures in cardiovascular health maintenance. We also explore age-related trends, contributing to a nuanced understanding of the aging cardiovascular system.

library(NHANES)
library(ggplot2)
library(logistf)

# Load NHANES dataset
data("NHANES")

# Select relevant variables
selected_vars <- c("Age", "BMI", "BPDiaAve", "BPSysAve", "PhysActiveDays", "TotChol", "TVHrsDay", "Weight")

# Subset the data with selected variables
subset_data <- NHANES[selected_vars]

# Remove rows with missing values
subset_data <- na.omit(subset_data)

Hypothesis We hypothesize that certain key indicators such as systolic blood pressure (BPSysAve) and total cholesterol (TotChol) will be significant factors in determining cardiovascular health. Additionally, we anticipate that age, physical activity, and BMI may also play crucial roles in understanding cardiovascular well-being.

Exploratory Data Analysis Scatter Plot Matrix To visualize the relationships between selected parameters, we created a scatter plot matrix focusing on Age, BMI, BPDiaAve, BPSysAve, PhysActiveDays, TotChol, TVHrsDay, and Weight. The scatter plot matrix allows us to observe potential trends and correlations among these variables.

# Descriptive statistics for selected variables

# Bivariate analysis for Age and BPSysAve
cor(subset_data$Age, subset_data$BPSysAve)
## [1] 0.5282125
# Scatter plot for Age and BPSysAve
ggplot(subset_data, aes(x = Age, y = BPSysAve)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of Age vs. BPSysAve",
       x = "Age",
       y = "Systolic Blood Pressure")

# Assuming BPSysAve and TotChol are relevant indicators for cardiovascular health
threshold_BPSysAve <- 120  # Example threshold for systolic blood pressure
threshold_TotChol <- 200  # Example threshold for total cholesterol

# Create a binary column named "CardioHealth" based on thresholds
subset_data$CardioHealth <- ifelse(subset_data$BPSysAve <= threshold_BPSysAve & subset_data$TotChol <= threshold_TotChol, 1, 0)

Logistic Regression Model A logistic regression model was fitted to predict cardiovascular health based on the selected parameters. The model provides insights into the influence of systolic blood pressure (BPSysAve) and total cholesterol (TotChol) on the likelihood of individuals having good cardiovascular health.

# Fit the logistic regression model using logistf
model <- logistf(CardioHealth ~ BPSysAve + TotChol, data = subset_data)
## Warning in logistpl(x, y, beta, i, LL.0, firth, -1, offset, weight, plcontrol,
## : fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred for variable (Intercept)

## Warning in logistpl(x, y, beta, i, LL.0, firth, 1, offset, weight, plcontrol, :
## fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred for variable BPSysAve
## Warning in logistpl(x, y, beta, i, LL.0, firth, -1, offset, weight, plcontrol,
## : fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred for variable TotChol
## Warning in logistpl(x, y, beta, i, LL.0, firth, 1, offset, weight, plcontrol, :
## fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred for variable TotChol
## Warning in logistf(CardioHealth ~ BPSysAve + TotChol, data = subset_data):
## Nonconverged PL confidence limits: maximum number of iterations for variables:
## (Intercept), BPSysAve, TotChol exceeded. Try to increase the number of
## iterations by passing 'logistpl.control(maxit=...)' to parameter plcontrol
# Add predicted values to the dataset
subset_data$Predicted_CardioHealth <- ifelse(predict(model, type = "response") > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Data visualization
# Scatter plot matrix for selected variables
scatter_matrix <- ggplot(subset_data, aes(x = Age, y = BMI, color = factor(CardioHealth))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of Age vs. BMI",
       x = "Age",
       y = "BMI",
       color = "Cardiovascular Health")

Boxplot of Systolic Blood Pressure (BPSysAve) A boxplot was generated to examine the distribution of systolic blood pressure (BPSysAve) among individuals with different cardiovascular health statuses. This provides insights into how systolic blood pressure varies between the two groups.

# Boxplot for BPSysAve
boxplot_bpsysave <- ggplot(subset_data, aes(x = factor(CardioHealth), y = BPSysAve)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Boxplot of BPSysAve by Cardiovascular Health",
       x = "Cardiovascular Health",
       y = "Systolic Blood Pressure")

Histogram of Total Cholesterol (TotChol) A histogram was created to visualize the distribution of total cholesterol (TotChol) in the dataset, differentiating between individuals with and without potential cardiovascular health concerns.

# Histogram for TotChol
hist_totchol <- ggplot(subset_data, aes(x = TotChol, fill = factor(CardioHealth))) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "identity", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Total Cholesterol by Cardiovascular Health",
       x = "Total Cholesterol",
       y = "Count",
       fill = "Cardiovascular Health")

Bar Plot of TV Hours per Day (TVHrsDay) A bar plot was generated to explore the distribution of TV hours per day (TVHrsDay) among the study participants. This provides insights into the sedentary behavior of the population.

# Bar plot for TVHrsDay
bar_tvhrsday <- ggplot(subset_data, aes(x = factor(TVHrsDay))) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Bar Plot of TVHrsDay",
       x = "TV Hours per Day",
       y = "Count")

Conclusion The scatter plot matrix, boxplot, histogram, and bar plot provide visual representations of the relationships between selected parameters and cardiovascular health. The logistic regression model enhances our understanding of the predictors of cardiovascular health in the studied population.
